{Partner's bid is a transfer asking you to bid 2\S, so you do. Partner now bids 3\H;   

Partner's bid is a transfer asking you to bid 2\S, so you do. Partner now bids 3\H;  

Partner is showing 5-5 in the Majors, with at least invitational strength. It's a close thing, but you decide to accept the invitation and bid 4\H.

The contract would be 4\H played by North.

South plays 4\H. West leads the \CJ. You play the \CQ. East wins with the \CA and plays the \HA then the \H3.

Loser List: \S = 1/2 : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 3/4

East trump play was good defense; it has prevented you from ruffing 2 \Ss in dummy. Even so your best plan will be to establish the \S suit.

So you next play \SK, \SA, then ruff a \S with dummy's \HQ. West does not follow to the third \S. 

Next play \DA and get to your hand by ruffing a \D. Pull the last trump, then give up a \S to East. Win his return, (by ruffing if necessary) and take your established \S winner and dummy's \CK. 

Suppose you had considered taking the \D finesse. It would have done you no good at all.

If it worked, all you could do would be to discard your fifth \S; but that was the \S that turned out to be a winner! 

It was the fourth \S that was a loser, and you couldn't get rid of that one.}
[Play "W"]CJ

